a:["$","div",null,{"className":"article-enter-delay-2","children":["$","div",null,{"className":"glass-card overflow-hidden mb-8 !hover:transform-none","children":["$","img",null,{"src":"/images/articles/swift-solar-buys-meyer-burger-tech-to-anchor-us-hj/main.jpg","alt":"Swift Solar Buys Meyer Burger Tech to Anchor US HJT Production","className":"w-full h-auto max-h-[400px] object-cover"}]}]}]
b:["$","div",null,{"className":"article-enter-delay-3 article-prose max-w-none","children":[["$","p",null,{"children":["The global solar supply chain just got a critical, if narrow, injection of American specificity. Swift Solar has acquired the heterojunction technology (HJT) intellectual property and key manufacturing assets from Switzerland's Meyer Burger, a move designed to bypass traditional polysilicon bottlenecks and establish genuine domestic cell production. This isn't merely an asset swap; it is a strategic maneuver to bring high-efficiency cell fabrication back to US soil, leveraging HJT's superior thermal performance over standard PERC architectures. For an industry obsessed with scale, this deal signals a pivot toward precision and supply chain resilience, even if the volume remains niche for now. You can read the initial breakdown in ",["$","a",null,{"href":"https://www.pv-magazine.com","children":"PV Magazine"}],"."]}],"\n",["$","div",null,{"className":"not-prose my-8 pt-6 border-t border-white/10","children":[null,["$","div",null,{"className":"glass-card overflow-hidden mb-4 !hover:transform-none","children":["$","img",null,{"src":"/images/articles/swift-solar-buys-meyer-burger-tech-to-anchor-us-hj/subtitle.jpg","alt":"The real cost of domestic solar cell manufacturing","className":"w-full h-auto max-h-[400px] object-cover"}]}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-text-secondary italic text-lg leading-relaxed font-medium","children":"The real cost of domestic solar cell manufacturing"}]]}],"\n",["$","p",null,{"children":["However, the devil lies in the yield curves and capital expenditure required to scale HJT outside of Asia's dominant ecosystem. While Meyer Burger struggled to make the economics work in Europe, Swift Solar bets that American policy incentives and a focused approach on next-gen perovskit-HJT tandems will unlock the efficiency gains that mass-market players have ignored. The immediate impact for utility developers is minimal, but for specialized commercial installers and defense microgrids, the promise of domestically produced, high-efficiency modules offers a compelling alternative to imported gear. Early signals suggest the transition will be slow, as retooling lines for HJT requires distinct equipment and processes compared to standard silicon cells. Further context on the technology shift is available via ",["$","a",null,{"href":"https://swiftsolar.com","children":"Swift Solar"}],"."]}]]}]
